However, the A.A. Step 11 reveals a complete lack of humility in A.A.:
<p>
<blockquote>
<font color="black" face="Lucida,Utopia bold,Utopia,Helvetica,Charter,Arial,sans-serif,Sans Serif,New Century Schoolbook">
11. Sought through prayer and meditation to improve our
conscious contact with God <i>as we understood Him</i>, praying only
for knowledge of His will for us and the power to carry that out.<br>
</font>
</blockquote>

<p>
This step is just some
<a href="orange-heresy.html#dabble_occult" target="_blank">dabbling in the occult</a>,
an attempt to &quot;channel&quot; God and hear the Voice of God in a s&eacute;ance.
<p>
<a name="Dinger"> </a>
This is all of course merely the repetition of the <i>Oxford Group</i> practice of &quot;Guidance&quot;,
where they believed that anyone could sit quietly for 15 minutes or an hour, and get a message
from God.  A Catholic theologian criticized that belief with these words:
<p>
<blockquote>
<font face="Lucida,Utopia bold,Utopia,Helvetica,Charter,Arial,sans-serif,Sans Serif,New Century Schoolbook">
What the <i>Group</i> has forgotten in all of this is that God ordinarily uses secondary causes
(public revelation as proposed by the Church, tradition, our own intellects, etc.) as
instruments for the attainment of truth. The Catholic, therefore, realizes that God does
not want us to set these lightly aside and seek truth directly and immediately from
His infinite knowledge. God wants us to seek Him, His Goodness and Truth, in all that
He has made and with all the means He has given us; otherwise, He has made all of these
in vain.
<p>
There is, indeed, a time for setting aside the use of our faculties and for practicing
the repose of passive prayer; but it is not at the beginning of the spiritual life. Such
a policy of action is wrong because it is based upon the presumption that each individual
has a proximate and individual call to the mystical life.<font size="-2"><sup>81</sup></font>
This attitude will inevitably lead to the errors of quietism, that infused contemplation
of the Infinite Truth and Goodness can be acquired at the beginning of the spiritual
life through one's own efforts and by the cessation of all operation,<font size="-2"><sup>82</sup></font>
How differently the prudent Catholic spiritual director acts, well and long trained in
the intricacies of theology and experienced in the guidance of souls. He realizes that
all souls are called in a general and remote manner to the mystical life,<font size="-2"><sup>83</sup></font>
but he does not presume to impose any soul upon the way of passive prayer (infused contemplation)
until definite signs of such an individual calling from God are provenly manifest.<font size="-2"><sup>84</sup></font>
<p>
Compare also the soul directed by the Catholic confessor secure in the truth of revealed Catholic
mystical and ascetical theology with the soul of the adherent of the <i>Group</i>,
insecure in the imaginings which come while listening for God's voice during a &quot;quiet time&quot;,
imposing themselves upon God with a daring which would have caused the saints to shudder!
<p>
But this is not all! It is not to the normal and ordinary divine intimacy of the mystical life
that MRA impels its members,<font size="-2"><sup>85</sup></font>
but to the extraordinary higher degrees!<font size="-2"><sup>86</sup></font>
And this is evident from what we have said about their expectation of divine
&quot;revelations.&quot; See this also in the light of Catholic teaching that humilty does not permit
one to aspire to these extraordinary degrees.<font size="-2"><sup>87</sup></font>
<p>
